04703nam a2200637Ia 9781501701009DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979585078  a97815017010097 a10.7591/97815017010092doi  a(DE-B1597)478475  a(OCoLC)923546368  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0370102bisacsh0481pa940qDE-1011 aCasteen, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom She-Wolf to Martyr :bThe Reign and Disputed Reputation of Johanna I of Naples /cElizabeth Casteen. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b7 halftones, 2 genealogies, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tGenealogies -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Murder of Andrew of Hungary and the Making of a Neapolitan She-Wolf -- t2. From She-Wolf to Radiant Queen: The Reign of Louis of Taranto and the Rehabilitation of Johanna of Naples -- t3. A Most Loving Daughter: Filial Piety and the Apogee of Johanna’s Reign -- t4. An “Especially Good Friend” to Saints: Friendship, Politics, and the Performance of Sovereignty -- t5. The Schism of the Western Church and the Division of Johanna of Naples -- tEpilogue -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1343 a seventeen-year-old girl named Johanna (1326–1382) ascended the Neapolitan throne, becoming the ruling monarch of one of medieval Europe's most important polities. For nearly forty years, she held her throne and the avid attention of her contemporaries. Their varied responses to her reign created a reputation that made Johanna the most notorious woman in Europe during her lifetime. In From She-Wolf to Martyr, Elizabeth Casteen examines Johanna's evolving, problematic reputation and uses it as a lens through which to analyze often-contradictory late-medieval conceptions of rulership, authority, and femininity.When Johanna inherited the Neapolitan throne from her grandfather, many questioned both her right to and her suitability for her throne. After the murder of her first husband, Johanna quickly became infamous as a she-wolf—a violent, predatory, sexually licentious woman. Yet, she also eventually gained fame as a wise, pious, and able queen. Contemporaries—including Francesco Petrarch, Giovanni Boccaccio, Birgitta of Sweden, and Catherine of Siena—were fascinated by Johanna. Drawing on a wide range of textual and visual sources, Casteen reconstructs the fourteenth-century conversation about Johanna and tracks the role she played in her time’s cultural imaginary. She argues that despite Johanna’s modern reputation for indolence and incompetence, she crafted a new model of female sovereignty that many of her contemporaries accepted and even lauded.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aQueenszItalyzNaples (Kingdom)vBiography. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aWomens Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aJoanna I of Naples, queenship, rulership, authority, femininity, female sovereignty, Johanna's public image, southern Italy, medieval Europe, medieval preconceptions about femininity, Italian history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170100940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701009423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701009/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  